# Security Review: `app.js`

I've reviewed the file. It's a small Express app (23 lines) with two endpoints: `/health` and `/users`. Here's a thorough security assessment against OWASP Top 10 and common Node.js pitfalls.

## Observed behavior

```js
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });
});

app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' },
  ]);
});

app.listen(3000, ...);
```

Both routes are GET-only, return static JSON, and take no user input — so many classic vulnerabilities (SQLi, command injection, XSS via reflected input, SSRF, path traversal, deserialization) are **not currently reachable**. That said, there are real issues and important hardening gaps.

---

## Findings

### 1. Sensitive data exposure — `/users` leaks PII without authn/authz (OWASP A01 / A02)
The endpoint returns email addresses to any unauthenticated caller. Even with mock data, this sets a dangerous pattern for when it's wired to a real DB.

**Recommendation:** require authentication and return only the fields the caller is authorized to see.

```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const header = req.get('authorization') || '';
  const token = header.startsWith('Bearer ') ? header.slice(7) : null;
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, { algorithms: ['HS256'] });
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  }
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  const users = [
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob',   email: 'bob@example.com'   },
  ];
  // Only expose email to the user themselves or admins.
  const safe = users.map(u =>
    (req.user.id === u.id || req.user.role === 'admin')
      ? u
      : { id: u.id, name: u.name }
  );
  res.json(safe);
});
```

### 2. No security headers (OWASP A05 – Security Misconfiguration)
Express ships with permissive defaults and leaks `X-Powered-By: Express`. Add `helmet` and disable the fingerprint header.

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 3. No rate limiting / DoS protection (OWASP A04 – Insecure Design)
`/health` and `/users` can be hammered without throttling. Add `express-rate-limit`:

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100, standardHeaders: true, legacyHeaders: false }));
```

Also set body-parser limits when you add POST/PUT later:
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '100kb' }));
```

### 4. No CORS policy declared (OWASP A05)
By default, Express doesn't set CORS headers — usually safe — but once a browser frontend is added, developers often enable `cors()` with no options, which sends `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`. Be explicit:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://app.example.com'], methods: ['GET'], credentials: false }));
```

### 5. `/health` exposes server time — minor information disclosure
`timestamp: new Date().toISOString()` is low-risk but the endpoint is often scraped to fingerprint uptime/clock skew. Consider returning only `{ status: 'ok' }` on the public health check and putting detailed diagnostics behind auth.

```js
